trigger.name: MySQL.General - Character Set of Server is utf8
trigger.description: The Character Set of your Server is utf8. This has performance impacts.

trigger.name: MySQL.General - Default Storage Engine is not InnoDB
trigger.description: Your Default Storage Engine is not set to InnoDB.

trigger.name: MySQL.General - General Log is enabled
trigger.description: Your General Log is enabled. If this is a production Server under high load, this is not recommended.

trigger.name: MySQL.General - Log Output is other than File
trigger.description: Your Log Output is not File. It can lead to problems when you run to Table for too long time.

trigger.name: MySQL.General - MySQL is down
trigger.description: MySQL database is down. This requires immediate action!

trigger.name: MySQL.General - Open files high
trigger.description: Open files is high. Please consider increasing open_files_limit.

trigger.name: MySQL.General - SQL Mode is very lazy
trigger.description:
Your SQL Mode is set very lazy (which is default). This is not necessarily what a professional DB developer wants. Some suggestions for sql_mode settings are:
* no_engine_substitution * full_group_by * traditional * ansi

trigger.name: MySQL.General - Table definition cache too small
trigger.description: Your Table Definition Cache is possibly too small. If it is much too small this can have significant performance impacts!

trigger.name: MySQL.General - Table open cache too small
trigger.description: Your Table Open Cache is possibly too small (old name Table Cache). If it is much too small this can have significant performance impacts!

trigger.name: MySQL.InnoDB- Deadlock detected
trigger.description: You got an InnoDB Deadlock. Please talk to your development department to fix this. Deadlocks are an application problem!

trigger.name: MySQL.InnoDB- Flush Log at Transaction Commit
trigger.description: ACID"1"commit & ) CA"2"commit & 1)

trigger.name: MySQL.InnoDB- Force Recovery is enabled
trigger.description: InnoDB Force Recovery is enabled. This mode should be used for data recovery purposes only. It prohibits writing to the data.

trigger.name: MySQL.InnoDB- Foreign Key error detected
trigger.description: You got an InnoDB Foreign Key error. Please talk to your development department to fix this.

trigger.name: MySQL.InnoDB- Log File size is too small
trigger.description: The InnoDB Log File size is possibly too small. Choosing a small InnoDB Log File size can have significant performance impacts.

trigger.name: MySQL.InnoDB- Plugin is enabled
trigger.description: InnoDB Plugin is enabled

trigger.name: MySQL.Master - Binary Log is disabled
trigger.description: Binary Log is disabled. This prohibits you to do Point in Time Recovery (PiTR).

trigger.name: MySQL.Master - Binlog Transaction Cache size too small
trigger.description: Binlog Transaction Cache size is possibly to small. A value of 1 Mbyte or higher is typically OK.

trigger.name: MySQL.Master - Default Binlog Format is not used
trigger.description: MySQL default "ROWS" but CA default "MIXED".

trigger.name: MySQL.Master - Sync Binlog is enabled
trigger.description: Sync Binlog is enabled. This leads to higher data security but on the cost of write performance.

trigger.name: MySQL.MPM - MPM Agent is down
trigger.description: MPM Agent was not reachable. We assume it is down!

trigger.name: MySQL.Slave - IO thread stopped
trigger.description: IO thread has stopped. This is usually because it cannot connect to the Master any more.

trigger.name: MySQL.Slave - Slave is NOT read only
trigger.description: Slave is NOT set to read only. You can accidentally manipulate data on the slave and get inconsistencies...

trigger.name: MySQL.Slave - Slave lagging behind Master
trigger.description: Slave is lagging behind Master. Please check if Slave threads are running and if there are some performance issues!

trigger.name: MySQL.Slave - SQL thread stopped
trigger.description: SQL thread has stopped. This is usually because it cannot apply a SQL statement received from the master.
